<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Rt Hon Sir Alan Beith</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Advocate</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Gordon Dawes on behalf of Kevin Delaney</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Crown Dependencies: Evidence of Lord McNally, 5 November 2013  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">I am writing to you on behalf of Mr Kevin Delaney, of Sark, who is managing director of Sark Estate Management Limited and, separately, editor and publisher of the Sark Newsletter.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Mr Delaney has studied closely the evidence of Lord McNally to the Committee and has instructed me to comment as follows:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Mr Delaney agreed with a great deal of what Lord McNally had to say concerning the state of Sark government.  He agrees entirely that Sark is not governed well.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">However there were several points that Mr</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> Delaney does take issue with.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Lord McNally said that Sark had (only) had democracy since the 2008 reforms (see answer to Q37 in the transcript).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Mr Delaney says that there is still no fully functioning democracy on Sark for the following reasons:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">there are no constituencies on Sark, all electors vote for all candidates, with the result that a majority interest group can dominate Chief Pleas completely, resulting in a single party state</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  If an interest group can muster sufficient votes to elect the last candidate to get into Chief Pleas then it follows you can select every successful candidate</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This is what has happened in Sark with the majority interest group consisting of those criticised elsewhere in L</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ord McNally's evidence as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">longing for the good old days of feudal rule, opposing reforms, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">opposing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">investment and even ideas;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Because of Sark's present constitution there is no opposition voice in Chief Pleas at all;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In reality Sark continues to have a feudal </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">constitution</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> because it continues to have a feudal lord at the head of its </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">constitution</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> and at the head of its property owning pyramid.  The Seigneur continues to have real political privileges and powers which nobody else has</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> by virtue only of inheriting land from his grandmother, which is entirely inappropriate according to the 21</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> century values which Lord McNally correctly said Sark must live by;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The Seigneur's privileges include the right to an unelected seat in Chief Pleas, the right to speak politically, extensive </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">powers of appointment/</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">dismissal form public office, a right of veto over certain legislation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">trusteeship of Sark's assets.  The Bailiwick's professional police force cannot even land on Sark without his permission, which is, quite frankly, outrageous;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Symbolic of his continuing power and influence is the fact that he sits, with no legal right to do so, on a large wooden throne on a dais overseeing every Chief Pleas meeting, with the President beside</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> him on a smaller wooden throne.  From this position the Seigneur makes speeches which set the tone for meetings; indeed his very presence and well known hostility to my client and the interests he represents is sufficient to set the tone of every meeting;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The President is the former Seneschal, appointed by the Seigneur in 2000, but now elected by the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">(one party) Chief Pleas members.  Lt. Col. Guille has displayed anything but neutrality in his role of speaker and has even been reprimanded by the Lt. Governor for his conduct;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The Seigneur continues to have considerable influence in addition to his actual powers.  He is the figurehead and rallying point for the people and viewpoints criticised by Lord McNally and, as noted above, he sits, unelected, in a dominant position in Chief Pleas making speeches from time to time which often set the tone for the entire meeting;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Sark is, in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">theory at least</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, governed by committees of Chief Pleas members, but those meetings are not open to the public nor are any minutes ever published.  The contrast with the way your own Committee works could not be starker;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">10</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The impression given is of government business being done behind closed doors and everything in Chief Pleas amounting to a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">fait accompli</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, a problem identified by Belinda Crowe in her report</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Government of Sark, Administrative and Executive Support</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 56.7pt 0pt 85.05pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The majority of detailed business is transacted not in Chief Pleas, but in its 16 committees.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Committee meetings are not open to the public and the minutes are not published. Although final</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">policy decisions are made by Chief Pleas sitting in full session, and full minutes of those debates</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">are published, the lack of time for detailed debate, and the often lack of substance in the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">explanatory papers, creates an impression that policies are decided behind closed doors, that the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">public have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">limited opportunity to input, and that many matters are voted through Chief Pleas ‘on</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the nod’.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">11</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Only very brief reports supporting propositions are ever published prior to Chief Pleas meetings and then only a short time before those meetings (the last meeting's agenda was dated 4</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> September and the meeting held on 2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> October, the previous agenda was dated 5</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> June for a 3</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> July meeting).  There is very seldom any active consultation on any proposition and very little time in which to make representations, let alone any prospect of having draft legislation amended in time for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> meeting; agendas commonly include draft legislation never seen before by the public and a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">re voted through at the meeting.  There is no equivalent to the various stages of a bill familiar to you and your colleagues of three readings, a committee stage a report stage and other pre-legislative scrutiny.  While this might be too much for a small assembly such as Sark, the present legislative process is wholly inadequate for true democracy to function;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">12</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Chief Pleas' rules of procedure are very brief and there is still no code of conduct for Conseillers, a basic register of interests is about to be adopted but the Seigneur and President have been exempted from having to make a return notwithstanding their status and influence in and over the assembly;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">13</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There is a perception that only those candidates acceptable to the establishment are ever elected.  Mr Delaney says that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Conseillers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> are selected rather than elected</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  This is again a function of the single and easily dominated constituency with no representation or protection of minority viewpoints</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 28.35pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">14</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Ultimately there are two conflicting systems of government on Sark, a still feudal establishment and the beginnings of a democratic system which cannot function properly because the feudal system remains largely intact, even to the extent of landholding remaining feudal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Mr Delaney also draws attention to the failure of Chief Pleas to implement the recommendations of Belinda Crowe's report </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">of May 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">(beyond appointing a Senior Administrator) or the recommendations of Colin Kniveton's reports (a senior Isle of Man civil servant who was seconded to Sark temporarily)</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Lord McNally commented critically on "some of the blogs that are alive in the island".  There is one principal such blog entitled "The blog of Ebenezer Le Page"</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">  I attach to this letter a copy of the posts relating to Lord McNally's evidence on a thread entitled "Listen up, Kevin".  The relevant sections have been highlighted for ease of reference.  Lord McNally is attacked as being </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">out of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">his</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> intellectual depth</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, an </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">even bigger impediment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">resolving Sark's problems than suspected, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">erring on the side of political expedience to cover his own estimable arse</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">", as having made a "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">very big error of misjudgement</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" which would "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">haunt him for a long time.  He has grotesquely overstepped the mark</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" and was an "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">old fraud</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" who should join a retirement community.  It was said that Lord McNally should "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">do us all a favour and retire himself</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">", "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">it ill behoves Tom (an unelected feudal Lord) to take a pop at Sark's residents in such a glib and inflammatory manner.  I suggest we all write to Sir Alan Beith and tell him he needs to press for Lord McNally's replacement asap</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Right</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Honourable Lord Tom McNally is a career politician – the very epitome of a Westminster Journeyman – rewarded from public funds …</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Please read him up, and then tell us what has ever occurred in his past to suggest that he has any relevance to the role he presently occupies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">"… "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">he is not elected.  Was a turncoat, an is "selected" as a member of feudal heritage.  Stop sucking up</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">After McNally's faltering performance … we should count nothing out</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">As we all expected, McNally's </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">naive</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Justice Committee folly is spun like a top</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Your Lordship, it is my sad duty to confirm the other views expressed herein, that it is time to make your excuses and go</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the only explanation can be that KD is still crawling up the MoJ fundament so that Tom continues to hand out spinnable quotes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Here we have … a reformed alcoholic PR man – all apparently in cahoots to undo the work of 448 years experience of operating a successful community.  Clearly the world has gone mad</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Rt Hon Lord Tom McNally, who appears to have no legal training, seems to have made a substantial error of judgement</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Good luck Ms Hannah, your clumsy boss has made your task – and ours – more difficult … Sark's very active </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">retirement</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> community would be pleased to welcome a new member</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">" … "</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">a 70 year old feudal "Lord" who is "bed-blocking" parliament and keeping out younger talent</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">".</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Mr Delaney suspects that posters on the Blog include leading members of the Sark establishment.  One Conseiller openly </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">identifies himself when posting and indeed another has taken recently to doing so also.  Blogs attacking Lord McNally have continued to the date of writing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">While Lord McNally was right to single out the blogs for criticism he made a serious error, in Mr Delan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ey's view, when commenting on the Sark Newsletter in the same breath and going so far as to suggest that it cease publication.  With all due respect to Lord McNally, the Sark Newsletter is a serious, weekly publication making serious political points and campaigning against precisely the same weaknesses and vested interests which Lord McNally identified in his own evidence.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">  It is the only opposition voice in Sark because there is none in Chief Pleas.  Mr Delaney makes no apology for its strident tone which reflects the treatment he has received at the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">hands of the Sark establishment and the bitter refusal of the establishment to reform Sark.  Lord McNally himself admitted to having to twist arms even to have an election observer appointed and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">noted </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the delay it took even to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">have Sark </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">respect an unappealed judgment of the English Court of Appeal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> on ECHR issues.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Nothing at all on Sark will change unless the feudal establishment is put under pressure.  If the Sark Newsletter ceased publication there would be no reforms.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">  Mr Delaney asserts his right to freedom of expression and the freedom of the press.  Such freedoms are especially important when under threat, as they are, in Sark.  Indeed a number of Conseillers and other members of the Sark establishment organised a march to his office with the intention of intimidating Mr Delaney into closing the Newsletter, something inconceivable in the United Kingdom.  It is precisely when unpopular views are being expressed that they most require protection.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Mr Delaney says that Sark will only be governed well and capable of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">receiving</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> a clean bill of health (to adopt Lord McNally's words) when its constitution is reformed further to remove the still dominant feudal elements.  It cannot be consistent with good governance and true democracy to have a feudal lord with very real powers at the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">heart of Sark's government and constitution</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Mr Delaney asks that this letter be included in the evidence to your Committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Yours sincerely</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gordon Dawes</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Partner &amp; Advocate</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">26 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Listen Up Kevin Blog Extracts: </span></p><p style="line-height:16.8pt; margin:18pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:2.4pt; text-transform:uppercase">Thursday, November 7, 2013</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><a name="_50362497045999000"></a><a href="http://ebenezerlepage.blogspot.com/2013/11/listen-up-kevin.html"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Listen up, Kevin</span></a></p><p style="line-height:19.2pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Lord McNally, at 10:38:20 in the video below:</span><br /><br /><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">'Let me be clear and I'll say again, as I've said to the Barclay brothers and to their representative, I wish that they would cease publication of the Sark Newsletter because I think it impedes getting the kind of empathetic relationships in Sark that would take the island forward...'</